<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-186-645  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 186 645  OV: 07 183 177.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  Jan 17 1989 v8 n1 p162(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Film recorders: ProColor. (Hardware Review) (one of 33 productevaluations included in PC Magazine's The Best of 1988)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fersko-Weiss, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Matrix Instruments Inc's ProColor film recorder costs only $5,995but produces slides of nearly the same quality as those fromhigh-end film recorders costing up to five times as much.andP;  TheProColor produces excellent slides in both 2Kbyte and 4Kbyteaddressable resolution, with clear text and no appreciablefuzziness in the curving lines.andP;  The film recorder has a paletteof over 16 million colors and can handle up to 256 colors at anygiven time.andP;  Attributes of ProColor include: digital recordingtechnology, a high-quality CRT, a seven-inch diagonal screen, andfine electronic control of focus, beam position and intensity.andO;ProColor's price increases to $7,990 with the addition of thecontroller board, but the buyer still gets high-quality slideoutput for under a low $8,000.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Matrix Instruments Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Matrix Instruments ProColor (Slide printer).andO;Topic:     EvaluationSlides (Photography)Presentation HardwareAchievements and Awards.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FILM RECORDERSandM;MATRIXandM;INSTRUMENTS INC.andM;ProColor Film recorders producing slides good enough for the corporateboardroom used to cost at least $15,000 to $50,000.andP;  Not anymore.andP;  MatrixInstruments' ProColor costs $5,995 ($7,990 with the controller board) andgives you slides of nearly the same quality as those from high-end filmrecorders costing two to five times as much.andM;The ProColor produces outstanding slides in either 2K or 4K addressableresolution.andP;  Text is sharp and clear, with no appreciable jaggedness orFuzziness in the curving lines.andP;  It can handle 256 colors on a slide at once,out of a palette of over 16 million.andP;  The colors are evenly saturated andbright, and there is almost banding of colors in a sweep background.andM;What makes the ProColor so good is a combination of digital recordingtechnology, a high-quality CRT--with a 7-inch-diagonal screen--and its fineelectronic control of focus, beam position, and intensity.andP;  It comes standardwith a Pentax 35mm camera but can also use a Polaroid 3 X 4 Instant Camera.andM;It's no surprise that Matrix has produced such a fine desktop filmrecorder--the company has been making high-end film recorders for 14 years.andO;Because the ProColor uses the same add-in board and software as Matrix's QCRand PCR, it is instantly supported by more than 30 graphics programs withdrivers for those models.andM;The ProColor has excellent documentation and the longest warranty period inthe market: 1 year.andP;  And you get high-quality slide output for under $8,000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>